Four years ago, Charlottesville, Virginia became the battleground for a clash between hate and decency. Neo-Nazis, Klansmen, and white supremacists gathered in the city, spewing antisemitic rhetoric and displaying violence reminiscent of Germany in the 1930s and Jim Crow America. However, they underestimated the power of American goodness. People of different races, religions, and backgrounds stood firm in their belief that everyone deserves equal treatment. One brave civil rights activist, Heather Heyer, lost her life in the fight against hate. Her death, along with the events in Charlottesville, motivated President Biden to run for office and continues to inspire his administration's efforts to eradicate hate in America. The President has taken action to advance racial equity, combat xenophobia against Asian Americans, and address hate crimes. The most recent example is the signing of the COVID-19 Hate Crimes Act, which aims to improve hate crimes reporting and accessibility. The President acknowledges that there is more work to be done, especially in light of the January 6th Capitol insurrection. He stresses the importance of confronting domestic terrorism rooted in white supremacy, which has been identified as the most significant threat to the nation. The Administration has implemented a comprehensive approach to address this issue, including countering online radicalization, disrupting hate group networks, and supporting communities in building resilience against hate. The President highlights the collective responsibility in this battle, citing the mobilization of various sectors and individuals in response to the events in Charlottesville. He emphasizes the need to tap into America's moral conscience and embrace our better angels to secure the soul of the nation.